2. Predicting Job Gains in the United States Solar Industry

All work (data collection, data cleaning, model creation, and prediction all done together by Javi and Priyanka)

1.1 ABSTRACT

Central to decarbonization is the timely, well-planned phase out of coal production. Currently, coal accounts for roughly a third of global energy supply and contributes 45% of global CO2 emissions. The worlds decarbonization pathway is clear, especially in the energy sector. Promising renewable technology like wind and solar power are the cheapest sources of energy compared to coal in most major countries. A central question is how to make this transition just - the workers that have powered our economy are facing job loss, structural economic transition, and uncertainty around the future of their work. The transition to low-carbon, environmentally and socially sustainable economies can be a strong driver of job creation, social justice and poverty reduction, if properly managed with the engagement of governments, workers, and unions. This project explores part of this question by using capacity, addition, retirement data for solar and coal as well as levelized costs of energy and state demographic data to predict potential job losses and job gains in the coal and solar industries respectively. We utilized state level employment data from the Bureau of Labor Statistics and the National Solar Jobs Census, nameplate capacity, capacity additions, capacity retirements, and LCOE data from the Energy Information Administration as well as demographic data for each state from the American Community Survey. We tested OLS, Ridge, Lasso, as well as Decision Tree Regression Models to identify the best fit for each fuel source. Based on our test scores, the Ridge Model with an R2 of .91 was the best model for solar, and a Ridge model as well with an R2 of .88 was the best model for coal. Ultimately, all of the models performed relatively well (test scores around or higher than 90%) so we chose to fit the coal and the solar models based on what score was highest. Our results were inherently associated with high variance because each dataset was tailored to fit each model based on fuel source however, we knew that this would be the case going into the project because our predictions were tailored to two different industries. We initially started off also hoping to create a model for wind, but ultimately could not find the data to build our dataframe.

1.2 PROJECT BACKGROUND

Central to decarbonization is the timely, well-planned phase out of coal production. Currently, coal accounts for roughly a third of global energy supply and contributes 45% of global CO2 emissions. The worlds decarbonization pathway is clear, especially in the energy sector. Promising renewable technology like wind and solar power are the cheapest sources of energy compared to coal in most major countries. Though the pace of this transition continues to fall behind net-zero targets, the clean energy transition seems inevitable, with renewable installation growth surpassing all projections. Coal industries across the world are financially insolvent, surviving only due to large subsidies by national governments, massive layoffs, and mechanization. The industry is associated with myriad community health, water pollution, and air pollution impacts, contributing to at least 800,000 premature deaths a year globally and many millions more illnesses. A central question is thus how to make this transition just - the workers that have powered our economy are facing job loss, structural economic transition, and uncertainty around the future of their work. The transition to low-carbon, environmentally and socially sustainable economies can be a strong driver of job creation, social justice and poverty eradication, if properly managed with the engagement of governments, workers, and unions.

Often coal communities that are most at risk of economic dislocation are geographically concentrated in a few parts of the country, with the coal industry a main economic activity and cultural identity for the community. Coal transitions in recent memory have seen significant drops in employment over a period of 10 years or less. However, transitioning thousands of employees into new employment cannot happen overnight. Thus, thoughtful planning and the proactive incorporation of opportunities of a renewable economy into a just transition are crucial to addresses fears of job loss and local economic decline. However, this also provides an opportunity to work creatively with communities to build new industries and employment opportunities. Moreover, it is increasingly clear that justice must be integral to the broader success of the climate movement. Without it, there can be no consensus between communities, sub-national, and national entities on the needed cooperation to mitigate and adapt to a climate changing world. This dynamic is evident at international negotiations like the UNFCC Conference of Parties, where developing and developed countries are often at a stalemate on climate cooperation because there is reticence from Western nations to shoulder historical responsibility and provide the funding needed for developing countries to successfully make the transitions away from fossil fuels.

In order to incorporate opportunities of a renewable economy, there must be reliable quantative analysis about the range of employment opportunities that are possible for countries and states to achieve through investment in growing the industry. At the same time, there also must be proactive planning to draw down industries like coal, and in order to do so it is important to understand how many jobs exist in the industry, how many are going to be lost and on what timescale. Understanding those trends, whether it be gains in renewables or losses in coal, can help support the interactions with communities to plan a just transition. It becomes very clear then what resources must be allocated to a region in order to re-skill workers, how much investment must be made in social safety nets to protect transitioning workers, and also identify the potential drivers of job growth in the renewables industry for that area.

Sources:

1.3 PROJECT OBJECTIVE

The purpose of this project is to train and evaluate different prediction models to assess job losses and job gains by state in the coal and solar industry respectively. In order to do this, we built two separate models - one for coal and one for solar. Below will be further detailed descriptions about the solar data, data cleaning, and solar models in this notebook and we will also be submitting a separate report for our coal model. This question will answer a three-part resource allocation that was elaborated on in the project background: What resources must be allocated to a region and on what timeframe to support coal workers, particularly in areas experiencing rapid job losses in the industry? What are the employment gains to be had from solar installations and how quickly is that industry growing in different regions? How many workers are affected by both transitions (towards solar and away from coal) and what implications does that have for resources allocated in terms of re-skilling, up-skilling, and broader economic diversification of a coal-dependent region?

In many cases the model shows that the job growth associated with investment in solar capacity is happening at an incredibly rapid pase. In part it was challenging to build this model because we couldn't find any previous examples of people using predictive modeling to answer these types of economic questions around employment in different energy sectors.

In order to build this model, we focused on temporal prediction in order to enable prediction of coal job loss or solar job gains in each state by year. In order to do this, we had to use a timelag of 1 year - if our prediction year was 2013, our features were pulled from 2012 data, 2014 with 2013, and so on. Important to note here is that some of our features included forecasted capacity additions and retirements by fuel source and that data was also pulled from the same year as the features. In other words, forecasts made in 2012 about capacity changes in subsequent years (we set it to be 7 years out) were also factored into our 1 year future predictions for 2013. This was done for each subsequent year and while we were able to use historical data for most of the training and testing for our model from years 2013-2021, we also had to use forecasted data for some features in our 2022 prediction given that we didnt have historical values for features like income, population, and educational statistics by state. To do this forecasting, we used the forecasting tool in Excel which also ran a linear regression to predict forecasted values based on previous trends. We understand that this makes our results potentially less credible but we believe that it can still provide a rough estimate of the features that we need in order to predict our y-variable (jobs).

1.4 INPUT DATA DESCRIPTION

The data that we used to build our solar model included the following -

  • National Solar Jobs Census by the Solar Industries Employment Association for historic employment (2012-2020) in the solar industry by state.
  • Energy Information Data from 2012-2020 on nameplate capacity from the previous year, as well as projected capacity, additions and retirements by state from the previous year. In order to find this data we used the Annual Energy Outlook, the Short Term Energy Outlook, Electric Power Monthly, Electric Power Annual, reported out from the EIA-860 forms.
  • Lazard data on levelized costs of energy for solar from 2012-2021. We assumed a constant LCOE for each state based on the yearly value.
  • American Community Survey and Historic US Census Data for demographic features including median household income, resident population, population above 25 years, population with educational attainments reaching high school, population with educational attainments reaching an associates degree, and population with educational attainments reaching a bachelor's degree.

SGSTF of Data Listed Above:

  • Structure: For each of our individual data sets (which we merged into one dataframe) the data is grouped by state and fuel source (for this model solar). Each observation in the data frame corresponds to a year and a state, and each column represents either our response variable data or our feature variable data for that state in that year. We downloaded all of these files as Excel files.
  • Granularity: Each row represents an observation from a state in each year from 2012-2020.
  • Scope: For our geographic scope, our data covers all states of the United States.
  • Temporality: Our data set covers the years between 2012-2020, and we predicted for the years 2021 and 2022. All predictions were done by state.
  • Faithfulness: Our demographic data comes from the Census Bureau, which is a government group that collects self-reported data on the population. Given that the data is self reported and voluntarily recorded, our data may be potentially skewed. Our National Solar Jobs Census data was collected and collated a private firm, BW Research Partnership, an independent energy employment research firm. This data seems up to date and reliable given that it is also used by the DOE for the US Energy Employment Report. Our Lazard data comes from historical averages and cross-validated with other LCOE estimates - little opportunities for data skewing. Finally, our EIA data came from multiple different datasets within the EIA database. Historic nameplate capacity data (for the previous year from our projection year) came from Electric Power Annual and our projected capacity additions and retirements came from the December version of Electric Power Monthly for years 2012-2020. For 2021 data (projecting 2022), we used the latest version of Electric Power Monthly which was released in October. We understand that this is an inconsistency in our data but unfortunately due to the fact that the December version has yet to be released yet, we had to rely on this data for our predictions. All of this data was originally downloaded catagorized by power plant (Form EIA-860) but we did some work in Excel first to sum by state the capacity, additions and retirements by state througn the use of a pivot table. This data is of course subject to change but because it is based on mandatory reporting at the power plant level, the data for the most part seems to be quite accurate in assessing solar capacity in the country.

1.5 and 1.6 - DATA CLEANING AND EDA

Our EDA is not in our coal and solar model files but can be found in a separate file which we plan to support along with this readout. However, here we will detail our process by which we conducted our Data Cleaning Process and our EDA. We separate these two things from our model notebook because our Cleaning and EDA process was so lengthy and complex. In order to conduct the EDA, we worked in Google Collab because we initially thought it would be easier for the two of us to work on code at the same time. However, this was not the case and we ultimately worked on code together from one computer and then inputted into the Google Collab sheet. Before we could merge the data into one dataset, we first needed to clean and conduct an EDA on the four components of our data: Jobs, Nameplate Capacity, Additions + Retirements, and Demographic Data (population, income, educational attainment).

Before we discuss the EDA portion, I'll first outline the ways in which we had to clean our data prior to even importing into a Google Collab notebook. Because there were multiple datasets that we needed to collate for each variable and because each dataset had a different granularity and temporality of features, for example EIA data being catagorized by power plant and demographic data by state, we had to prep a lot of our datasets first in excel in order to get all variables defined by state and year. This included primarily collating yearly datasets into one large dataset and using pivot tables to sum up variables like namelpate capacity, historic addition and retirement as well as projected addition and retirement data by state and year (vs power plant). We also downloaded the full American Community Survey Census Data and created a new dataframe by pulling the specific columns that we wanted to include as demographic information for the years 2012-2020.

There are four components to our EDA file:

1. EDA Jobs 2. EDA Nameplate + Demographic 3. EDA Solar Ret & Add 4. EDA Coal Ret & Add (Not Relevant for Solar Model)

EDA Jobs: In this section of the EDA, we downloaded into the notebook the jobs data from 2012-2020 which we had downloaded into one spreadsheet from the source. It was easy to manage this section because the dataset was already formatted by state and year and totalled.

EDA Nameplate and Demographic: In this section we imported the demographic data by state and year which we had pulled originally from the very large American Community Survey Dataset and pulled the specific columns that we wanted to use as demographic data - median household income, resident population, population over the age of 25, educational attainment levels for high school, associate degree and bachelors degree. In excel we had compiled all that data for each year and state and imported it into our notebook. Similarly, for nameplate capacity data we used the datasets from EIA and did a pivot table to get the summed nameplate capacity data by state and year (using the 8 different datasets). We then uploaded this into our notebook as well. and merged it with the dataframe from Step 1. The output of these steps is a coal dataframe including dataframe (coal and solar) with jobs, nameplate capacity and demographic information for each state, in each year from 2012 to 2020.

EDA Retirement and Additions: There are two parts to this but I will only focus on the solar retirements and additions for this part of the writeup. Firs thing to note is that there were minimal if none at all solar retirements for all the years studied so ultimately our dataframe only included additions columns and no retirement columns. Historic additions were first identified in excel and used a pivot table to sum up the additions by state and year. We then uploaded those files into our notebook and appended it onto the existing dataframe which at that point contained jobs, nameplate capacity, and demographic information. This was defined as "N Additions" where N represented the lagged year that we used to predict the subsequent year. For example, N additions for the year 2013 were the additions for 2012. For Projected Additions, we did a similar process first creating "N+1", "N+2"...until "N+7" columns. For clarity this meant that in the case of year 2013, "N+1" represented the projected additions for solar made in 2012 for the year 2013. We did this for all subsequent years. In order to do this, we had to create a for loop that took our datasets from Excel which had totalled the projections by year and state and then the code was used to match to the state and prediction year in our larger dataframe.

At the end we added a column for our LCOE which was constant by state for each year. This dataset had already been copied and prepped previously in Excel so we just merged to our dataframe. The result was the final dataframe which we then used to build and train our model.

def fit_OLS(X,y):
    X_const = sm.add_constant(X)
    ols_model = sm.OLS(y,X_const)
    results = ols_model.fit()
    return results.summary()

from sklearn.model_selection import LeaveOneOut
loo = LeaveOneOut()
loo.get_n_splits(X)
y_tests = []
y_predictions = []

for train, test in loo.split(X): 
    Xr_train, Xr_test = np.array(X)[train], np.array(X)[test] 
    yr_train, yr_test = np.array(y)[train], np.array(y)[test] 
    
    lr = LinearRegression()
    lr.fit(Xr_train, yr_train)
    yr_pred = lr.predict(Xr_test) 
    
    y_tests.append(yr_test[0][0]) 
    y_predictions.append(yr_pred[0][0]) 

r2_loo = r2_score(y_tests, y_predictions)
MSE_loo = np.exp(mean_squared_error(yr_test, yr_pred))
print("R^2 after LOOCV: ", r2_loo)
print("OLS MSE after LOOCV: ", np.exp(MSE_loo))

def fit_model(SKL_model, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test, alpha = 1):
 
    
    if SKL_model==LinearRegression():
        model != SKL_model()
        model.fit(X_train, y_train)
        model.coefficients = model.coef_
        y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    else:
        model = SKL_model(alpha)
        model.fit(X_train, y_train)
        model.coefficients = model.coef_
        y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
           
   
    mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
    coef = model.coef_.flatten() 
    return mse, coef

def importance_plot(tree):
    # YOUR CODE HERE
    feature_importance = pd.DataFrame({'Feature': X.columns, 'Importance': first_tree.feature_importances_}) # get the importance of each feature
    
    #calculate the relative feature importances 
    relative_importance = ((feature_importance['Importance'])/0.58004)*100
    
    # Save to a dataframe with two columns: One holding the names of the features, 
    # and one holding the associated relative importance of each feature.
    feat_df = pd.DataFrame({'feature':X_train.columns, 'importance':relative_importance})
    
    # Sort feat_df in order of importance
    feat_df = feat_df.sort_values(by='importance', ascending=True)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(20, 50))
    
    # Create a bar chart. The widths of the bars should correspond to the importances, 
    # and y should correspond to the names of the features. 
    plt.barh(width= feat_df['importance'], y=feat_df['feature'])
    plt.xlabel('Relative feature importance');

Interpretation and Conclusions¶

Our results indicate that our feature variables have some predictive power to predict our response variables for our solar model as well. Similar to the coal model, it is important to first address the fact that set our y variable array was defined as the log of our response variables because many of our data inputs had 0s thus affecting our distribution (seen in the histogram above). Our data had many zeros in part because there weren't projections of capacity additions and retirements for every state. When getting our results for our predictions we had to first take the exponent of our values to cancel out the log. Unlike the coal model, the employment numbers for the solar industry aren't trending downwards, so results are pretty self-explanatory.That being said, its interesting to note how rapidly solar jobs are growing, even in areas that are historically invested in fossil fuels. For example, our model predicts that Texas will see solar job growth from 30,000 in 2021 to 37,000 in 2022. The minimum number of predicted jobs is found in Alabama (around 99) and the maximum number of predicted jobs in the coming years can be found in California (over 100,000).

Based on our model tests, as outlined above, we chose to conduct our predictions using a Leave One Out Cross-Validated Ridge because the R2 score was highest when comparing all of the parametric models that we tested. Like the coal model, all of the models gave us very high test scores but we chose to use the Ridge model because it had an over .9 r2 square as well as the lowest MSE score. Using this model, we were able to see that in contrast to the coal model, solar job growth are happening at a rapid pace. As part of resource allocations around a just transition, it is incredibly important to make sure that investments are happening for renewable energy industries, especially in communities that are particularly coal dependent. Economic diversification and retraining policies will be critical in ensuring that communities dependent on coal are able to reap the clear employment gains that come from the renewable industry, and the expected growth in the industry as showcased by our moddel. Without that intentional allocation of resources, the growth of the renewables industry across states will occur but benefits will potentially not reach the communities that are most affected by the transition, creating economic dislocation for concentrated coal communities. I would recommend that policymakers at a state and federal level invest resources in these communities and also provide them with opportunities in either new energy industries or broader opportunities for regional economic diversification. Currently, very few resources are allocated towards just transition policies in the United States but with our model, understanding the timeframe and rapidity of potential coal job loss, policymakers could begin to conduct proactive planning around supporting coal-dependent communities and investing in reskilling resources for workers to participate in the renewables industry if they want to. We hope that readers will also care about our results, understanding that the economics of the solar industry are robust.

Our results should be taken into account with a few caveats: first, our data was based on historical as well as forecasts for the future. While the EIA is a trusted source for these types of projections, some of the additions and retirements that are projected by the Agency are not necessarily guaranteed to be retired (or added). Second as discussed in the data sections above, our demographic data is based on self-surveys which automatically means potential skewing of the data. Moreover, for our 2022 predictions we also had to use Excel forecasted values of demographics for 2021. Unlike our coal model, the jobs data that we trained our response variable on seems to be accurately reported since its source comes from the US solar trade association which implies potentially more accurate data. As mentioned in our coal model writeup, our feature data for solar also does clearly have some significant relationship to employment because all of our model testing had high validation scores across different types of models - OLS, Ridge and Lasso, and all of the tree models. Our model also falls within the bias variance tradeoff by potentially having high variance but it is interesting that the solar and coal models use the Ridge method for both predictions, which has implications for the potential external validity of the model.
